n\\\'s South End, photo scavenger hunt, and community service project at a local soup kitchen.','The FUP introduces incoming freshman to MIT and the Cambridge and Boston community via community service and discussions of urban issues.','Community agencies and partners may apply to receive volunteers from the FUP program during the summer. If you are interested, please contact the MIT Public Service Center.','Kristi Gundrum Kebinger','MIT Public Service Center','77 Massachusetts Avenue, 4-104\nCambridge, MA 02144','617-253-0742','kristig@mit.edu','FUP Planning Committee','MIT Public Service Center','77 Massachusetts Avenue, 4-104\nCambridge, MA 02144','617-253-0742','fup-staff@mit.edu','Kristi Gundrum Kebinger','77 Massachusetts Avenue 4-104\nCambridge, MA 02144','617-253-0742','fup-staff@mit.edu','','','','','http://web.mit.edu/mitpsc/volunteering/programs/fup/','','psc_logo_print_color.png',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'sample9.jpg',NULL,'2010-04-16','2010-04-16','2010-04-16','2010-04-16','2010-04-16','2010-04-16','2010-04-16','2010-04-16','2010-04-16','2010-06-28','2010-04-16','2010-04-16','2010-04-16','2010-06-28','2010-04-16','2010-06-28','2010-04-16','2010-06-28','2010-04-16','2010-04-16','2010-04-16','2010-04-16','2010-04-16','2010-06-28','2010-06-28','2010-04-16',6,'0','0','0','1','0','0','MIT Public Service Center',NULL,'2010-04-16','0','','MIT Public Service Center','2010-04-16','2010-04-16',NULL,NULL),(29,'Tuberculosis Treatment & Prevention Project, India','The Tuberculosis Treatment & Prevention Project was launched in June 2005 and aims for the eradication of this deadly but easily curable disease. Our first target is the poor villages in the State of Bihar in India. We need people who can help us in any way from medical assistance to fundraising to web management. We are currently looking for computer programmers to help with a web based medical assessment program that we are currently developing with MIT students and researchers to be used in India. These programs are run by MIT Prajnopaya and the Prajnopaya Foundation in India.','The Tuberculosis Treatment & Prevention Project was launched in June 2005 and aims for the eradication of this deadly but easily curable disease. ','This program is free.','Tenzin Priyadarshi Skukla','Religious Life','W11-063','617-253-8968','kristig@mit.edu','MIT Prjnopaya mailing list','Religious Life','W11-063','617-253-0742','volunteerplacement@mit.edu','Cristina Garcia Colina','60 Hartwell Road\nCarlisle, MA 01741','617-395-4201','kristig@mit.edu','','','','','http://www.prajnopaya.org/found_index/htm','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-16','2010-04-16',NULL,6,'0','0','0','0','0','0','MIT Prajnopaya',NULL,'2010-04-05','0','','','2010-04-05','2010-04-05',NULL,NULL),(30,'Public Service Fellowships','The Fellowships programs supports MIT students working on capacity-building service projects around the world. Fellows  work with community-focused organizations such as non-profits, government offices, international aid agencies, schools, grassroots groups, student-initiated service enterprises and even for-profit businesses if the business is using a social-entrepreneurship model to address the needs of an under-served community. Students in these programs receive a stipend for their work, which typically goes towards living and travel expenses.','The Fellowships programs supports MIT students working on capacity-building service projects around the world.','Public Service Fellows play a leading role in developing and implementing their service projects. Fellows must work in collaboration with a supervisor in a community organization that will benefit from their work in the long term but Fellows typically take a consultant or partnership role with their supervisors, rather than working directly for them. MIT students who are developing their own non-profits or social enterprises may also apply for Fellowships to support them in this process.','Alison Hynd','Public Service Center, Fellowships Administrator','77 Massachusetts Avenue, W20-549\nCambridge, MA 02139','617-258-0691','hynd@mit.edu ','Sally Susnowitz','Public Service Center','77 Massachusetts Ave., 4-104\nCambridge, MA 02139','617-253-0742','fellowships-staff@mit.edu','Alison Hynd','77 Massachusetts Avenue, W20-549\nCambridge, MA 02139','617-258-0691','hynd@mit.edu ','','','','','http://mit.edu/mitpsc/resources/internshipsandfellowships/index.html','hussain-johnson.jpg','scolnik_businesswheelchair1.jpg.png',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2010-06-28','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-09','2010-06-28','2010-06-28','2010-06-28','2010-06-28','2010-06-28','2010-06-28','2010-04-05','2010-06-28','2010-06-28','2010-06-28','2010-06-28','2010-06-28','2010-06-28','2010-06-28','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-06-28','2010-06-28','2010-04-07',6,'0','0','0','1','0','0','MIT Public Service Center',NULL,'2010-06-28','0','','Public Service Center','2010-04-05','2010-04-05',NULL,NULL),(31,'Youth Astronomy Apprenticeship','The Youth Astronomy Apprenticeship (YAA) program is an out-of-school time (OST) initiative that uses an astronomy apprenticeship model to promote learning in STEM disciplines among urban, underrepresented youth and their communities. After a training period during the school year, a promising group of students is selected to participate in the Summer Youth Apprenticeship Program that is based at MIT. During the summer, the youth are mentored and supervised by YAA Fellows and work with experts in the field. The task of the apprentices is to create a portfolio of astronomy and science outreach events, during which they will present astronomy and science content to audiences from their local communities.','The Youth Astronomy Apprenticeship program uses an astronomy apprenticeship model to promote learning among urban, underrepresented youth.','Summer apprenticeships for 2010 will be offered to students who are currently attending the ASAP program at these organizations: Dimock Community Health Center, Urban League of Eastern MA, Roxbury Multi-Service Center, John D. O\'Bryant Youth Center, Tobin/Mission Hill Community.','Dr. Irene Porro','Astrophysics','77 Massachusetts Avenue, NE80-6095\nCambridge, MA 02139','617-258-7481','kristig@mit.edu','Dr. Irene Porro','Astrophysics','77 Massachusetts Avenue, NE80-6095\nCambridge, MA 02139','617-258-7481','kristig@MIT.EDU','Dr. Irene Porro','77 Massachusetts Avenue, NE80-6095\nCambridge, MA 02139','617-258-7481','kristig@mit.edu','','','','','http://yaa.mit.edu',NULL,'',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05','2010-04-05',NULL,NULL,6,'0','0','0','0','0','0','MIT Kivali Institute for Astrophysics and Space Research',NULL,'2010-04-05','0','','','2010-04-05','2010-04-05',NULL,NULL),(33,'Families Accessing Computer Technology','FACT helps to bridge the Digital Divide by offering an introductory 6-week course that covers computer hardware, word processing, spreadsheet, internet browsing and e-mail applications. Each volunteer is matched with a family and works exclusively with them for two hours per week on Saturday mornings for half a semester. Volunteers will gain invaluable communication and tutoring skills as well as get a new perspective on how technology can be used to help the local community. While a formal curriculum is provided for the classes, the nature of the program allows the teachers and clients to decide on which topics they would prefer to focus. No previous computer or teaching experience is necessary. FACT is sponsored by the Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence department\\\'s Imara program.','FACT helps to bridge the Digital Divide by offering an introductory 6-week course that covers basic computer use skills for community members. ','The program meets on Saturdays','Jason Dorfman','CSAIL/Imara','77 Massachusetts Avenue, 32-268\nCambridge, MA 02139\n','(617) 253-1150','kristig@mit.edu','Kristi Gundrum Kebinger','PSC','4-104','617-253-0742','volunteerplacement@mit.edu','Jason Dorfman','77 Massachusetts Avenue, 32-268\nCambridge, MA 02139\n','(617) 253-1150','kristig@mit.edu','','','','','http://imara.csail.mit.edu/?q=node/36','11.jpg','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07',NULL,6,'0','0','0','0','0','0','CSAIL Imara',NULL,'2010-04-07','0','','CSAIL/Imara','2010-04-07','2010-04-07',NULL,NULL),(34,'High School Studies Program (HSSP)','HSSP is an MIT Educational Studies initiative offering non-credit, enrichment courses to 7th-12th grade students for the astonishingly low fee of $30 for an entire semester. The program, held on (sorry, kids) Saturdays in MIT\'s famous \"infinite corridor,\" is designed to give teenage students the opportunity to explore a variety of both academic and non-academic subjects. Each year, courses are developed out of the particular interests of that year\'s teachers. In past years, courses have ranged from Latin to calculus to choreographed hip hop and jazz appreciation. Students choose their own courses based on their interests. HSSP runs twice a year, once in the Spring semester for 10 Saturdays (usually late February through the end of April), and once over the summer, usually in alternating years on Saturdays, and on weeknight evenings, running for 6 to 8 weeks. ','HSSP is an MIT Educational Studies initiative offering a wide variety of non-credit, enrichment courses to 7th-12th grade students.','Summer HSSP begins in June.','David Fahri','ESP','450 Memorial Drive\nCambridge, MA 02139','617-253-4882','volunteerplacement@mit.edu','Kristi Gundrum Kebinger','PSC','4-104','617-253-0742','kristig@MIT.EDU','David Farhi','450 Memorial Drive\nCambridge, MA 02139','617-253-4882','volunteerplacement@mit.edu','','','','','http://esp.mit.edu','79.jpg','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07',NULL,6,'0','0','0','0','0','0','Educational Studies Program (ESP)',NULL,'2010-04-07','0','','ESP','2010-04-07','2010-04-07',NULL,NULL),(35,'Lemelson-MIT InvenTeams','InvenTeams is the Lemelson-MIT Program\'s national initiative to foster inventiveness among high school students. We ask teams, composed of students, teacher(s) and mentors, to identify a problem to address with an invention, and then fund them up to $10,000 ($2,000 can be a teacher stipend) to develop a prototype. Previous projects include consumer products (e.g.: a watermelon ripeness evaluator -see photo at right), assistive devices (e.g.: a barcode-to-voice device for the visually impaired), health/safety devices (e.g.: a remote control helicopter for avalanche detection), and environmental tools (e.g.: a water monitoring device). All projects must be student-driven and any resulting intellectual property belongs to the students. Teachers are brought to MIT in the fall for a workshop on invention, and teams are invited to MIT in June to showcase their projects. ','InvenTeams is the Lemelson-MIT Program\'s national initiative to foster inventiveness among high school students.','Applications are available in October for the following academic year. Grants run from October to June.','Leigh Estabrooks','Lemelson-MIT Program','77 Massachusetts Avenue, E60-215\nCambridge, MA 02139','617-253-3352','volunteerplacement@mit.edu','Kristi Gundrum Kebinger','Public Service Center','4-104','617-253-0742','kristig@MIT.EDU','Leigh Estabrooks','77 Massachusetts Avenue, E60-215\nCambridge, MA 02139','617-253-3352','volunteerplacement@mit.edu','','','','','http://web.mit.edu/inventeams','60.jpg','60.jpg.jpg',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07',6,'0','0','0','0','0','0','Lemelson-MIT Program',NULL,'2010-04-07','0','','Lemelson-MIT Program','2010-04-07','2010-04-07',NULL,NULL),(36,'Keys to Empowering Youths (KEYs)','KEYs is a motivational program that brings 11 to 13 year old girls together with MIT women students to participate in workshops held periodically throughout the school year and once over the summer. The goal of KEYs is to empower young women by promoting their self-confidence, increasing their self-esteem, and unveiling opportunities for their potential career paths. Girls are encouraged to take a closer look at science and its impact on society. Workshops such as \"Moving Beyond Stereotypes,\" \"Women\'s Health and Medicine,\" and \"The Environment and You,\" are designed to excite girls about science and inspire them to think about their lives in new ways. By showing girls what possibilities exist in their own lives, KEYs strives to help them develop their own goals and dreams. Girls ages 11-13 are at the center of a critical educational dilemma in the United States. ','KEYs is a motivational program that brings 11-13 yr old girls together with MIT women students to participate in workshops about science.','Educational bias, gender-based preconceptions, and stereotypes leave girls with diminished self-esteem.','Nour Abdul-Razzak','Society of Women Engineers','77 Massachusetts Avenue, 4-104\nCambridge, MA 02139','617-225-8629','volunteerplacement@mit.edu','Kristi Gundrum Kebinger','Public Service Center','77 Massachusetts Avenue, 4-104\nCambridge, MA 02139','617-253-0742','kristig@MIT.EDU','Nour Abdul-Razzak','77 Massachusetts Avenue, 4-104\nCambridge, MA 02139','617-225-8629','volunteerplacement@mit.edu','','','','','http://web.mit.edu/swe/www/index.html','fall09part4_103.png','keys_logo.gif',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-07','2010-04-16','2010-04-07','2010-04-07',6,'0','0','0','0','0','0','Society of Women Engineers',NULL,'2010-04-07','0','','Society of Women Engineers','2010-04-07','2010-04-07',NULL,NULL),(37,'Women\'s Technology Program','The Women\'s Technology Program (WTP) is a four-week summer residential program at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology to introduce female high school students to Electrical Engineering and Computer Science (EECS) or Mechanical Engineering (ME). These academic programs enable students to explore engineering through hands-on, team-based projects. Female MIT graduate students teach the classes. Selected participants have excellent grades in advanced high school math and science classes and PSAT, ACT, or SAT math test scores in the 75th percentile or higher. Sixty students (40 for EECS, 20 for ME) are admitted each year from a nationwide applicant pool of female 11th grade high school students. Students must reside in the U.S. or be U.S. citizens if living outside the U.S. The fee for participating students is $3,000, which includes housing, food, classes, books, lab materials, and group activities for the 4-week program. Financial assistance is available. ','The Women\'s Technology Program is a 4-week summer residential program at MIT to introduce female high schoolers to electrical & mechanical engineering','WTP-EECS Curriculum: 3 classes in CS, EE, & Discrete Math. CS: introduces students to problem solving and Java programming. EE: teaches basics of digital and analog electronics. Math: topics include probability, recursion, combinatorics, logic, and algorithms. WTP-ME Curriculum: Integrated classes in Mechanical Engineering and Applied Math combine hands-on work with analytical calculations. Topics include fluid mechanics, materials, statics, thermodynamics, and engineering design.','Cynthia Skier','EECS','MIT Room 38-491\nCambridge, MA 02139','617-253-5580','volunteerplacement@mit.edu','Kristi Gundrum Kebinger','Public Service Center','77 Massachusetts Ave, 4-104\nCambridge, MA 02